		<div id="comment-150289">
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/08c73cf5cce9116bcdcf822c9a7b2919?s=48&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />
			<cite class="fn"><a href='http://thesparrk.blogspot.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>sparrk</a></cite>

			<span class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				|
				<a href="http://www.thesurvivalpodcast.com/permaculture-misconception-vs-reality/comment-page-1#comment-150289">
				December 15, 2011 at 9:57 pm</a>
					|
													</span><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-body"><p>Great points you make in this show. One thing I&#8217;d like to correct, though, is that on diversified, homestead-style farms &#8211; including permaculture farms &#8211; you may not need as much hired labor at harvest as you think. This is because diversified farmers will tend to structure their farm enterprises to employ people year round or close to it (mostly their own family, traditionally). So they&#8217;ll have the labor necessary on site to handle the harvest. 4 acres of corn is not an overwhelming amount for a family, or a couple hired guys, and the that labor can be kept employed the rest of the year at other tasks due to the diversity of on-farm operations; e.g. livestock, forestry, fiber, homestead activities (fixing the roof), etc. I&#8217;ve been breaking this down on my blog, researching the traditional economics of peasant farming. That&#8217;s really the model &#8211; minus serfdom &#8211; that you&#8217;re talking about replicating. It&#8217;s legit. Here&#8217;s where I respond to your episode: <a href="http://thesparrk.blogspot.com/2011/12/first-application-of-peasant-economics.html" rel="nofollow">http://thesparrk.blogspot.com/2011/12/first-application-of-peasant-economics.html</a></p>
</div>

	</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		</ol>

		
	
			
</div><!-- #comments -->
			
			</div><!-- #content -->
		</div><!-- #content-container -->


